<ZT2Strings>
      <LOC_STRING _locID="zoopedia_eucalyptus:entry"  >Eucalyptus Leaves</LOC_STRING>
      <LOC_STRING _locID="zoopedia_eucalyptus:text"  >
         <cell pady="40" width="1000"/>
         <p/>
         <cell width="260"/>
         <cell width="640" height="320" bgimg="ui/zoopedia/topCellBg.dds">
            <cell width="600" padx="20" pady="20">
               <color r="255" g="255" b="255">
                  <img src="entities/objects/food/Terrain_df/TerrainEucalyptus_df_icon.dds" sx="0" sy="0" sw="64" sh="64"/>
                  <p/>
Although eucalypus trees are abundant throughout Australia, their leaves are tough, low in nutrition, and contain oils that are poisonous to most animals. Few species eat eucalpytus; however, there is one animal that lives almost exclusively on the fragrant leaves: the    
                  <a href="zoopedia:zoopedia_koala:entry">
                     <u>
                        <color r="255" g="231" b="135">koala</color>
                     </u>
                  </a>
. The koala's body is specially adapted to process the eucalyptus toxins, while the koala's sluggish metabolism helps compensate for the low nutrition value of eucalyptus. 
                  <p/>
Eucalypus leaves can be placed directly on the ground, in a food dish, or in an elevated food dish.    
               </color>
            </cell>
         </cell>
      </LOC_STRING>
      <LOC_STRING _locID="zoopedia_berries:entry"  >Berries</LOC_STRING>
      <LOC_STRING _locID="zoopedia_berries:text"  >
         <cell pady="40" width="1000"/>
         <p/>
         <cell width="260"/>
         <cell width="640" height="320" bgimg="ui/zoopedia/topCellBg.dds">
            <cell width="600" padx="20" pady="20">
               <color r="255" g="255" b="255">
                  <img src="entities/objects/food/Terrain_df/TerrainBerries_df_icon.dds" sx="0" sy="0" sw="64" sh="64"/>
                  <p/>
A wide variety of animals enjoy the sweet taste of berries, including the     
                  <a href="zoopedia:zoopedia_peafowl:entry">
                     <u>
                        <color r="255" g="231" b="135">peafowl</color>
                     </u>
                  </a>
, the                   
                  <a href="zoopedia:zoopedia_chimp:entry">
                     <u>
                        <color r="255" g="231" b="135">chimpanzee </color>
                     </u>
                  </a>
and the 
                  <a href="zoopedia:zoopedia_lemur:entry">
                     <u>
                        <color r="255" g="231" b="135">ring-tailed lemur</color>
                     </u>
                  </a>
. Even the carnivorous
                  <a href="zoopedia:zoopedia_grizzly:entry">
                     <u>
                        <color r="255" g="231" b="135">grizzly bear </color>
                     </u>
                  </a>
  sometimes eats berries to supplement its diet.                  
                  <p/>
Berries can be placed directly on the ground, in a food dish, or in an elevated food dish. They can also be hidden in substrate piles or hollow logs to encourage animals to explore. 
               </color>
            </cell>
         </cell>
      </LOC_STRING>

</ZT2Strings>
